WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:04.900
RANGA KRISHNAN: I'm Ranga Kr

00:00:05.010 --> 00:00:07.710
ishnan with Solidarity Social.

00:00:07.760 --> 00:00:10.300
So I'm not going to talk too much about the why

00:00:10.300 --> 00:00:10.500
.

00:00:10.500 --> 00:00:12.480
I'll leave it to the questions.

00:00:12.480 --> 00:00:14.600
I'm going to mostly go into what.

00:00:14.600 --> 00:00:16.400
But if you want to look at some of the why,

00:00:16.400 --> 00:00:18.820
Solidarity Social is the website.

00:00:18.820 --> 00:00:21.020
It'll probably answer a lot of questions.

00:00:21.020 --> 00:00:23.800
So with that, I want to get into what has been

00:00:23.800 --> 00:00:25.760
built and what it is.

00:00:25.760 --> 00:00:28.260
Too little time to do a live demo, so I recorded

00:00:28.260 --> 00:00:28.720
it.

00:00:28.720 --> 00:00:30.800
I'm going to start it here.

00:00:30.800 --> 00:00:35.270
And so the cast of characters, this is the Solidarity

00:00:35.270 --> 00:00:36.860
Social account.

00:00:36.860 --> 00:00:42.950
This is a user that is on bSkySocial

00:00:42.950 --> 00:00:44.880
, the regular network.

00:00:44.880 --> 00:00:52.530
And the first part is that-- keep an eye on this

00:00:52.530 --> 00:00:53.800
list.

00:00:53.800 --> 00:00:56.120
These are the six parts I'm going to go through.

00:00:56.120 --> 00:00:57.440
The first part is the pre-boarding.

00:00:57.440 --> 00:01:00.240
How does somebody get an invite code?

00:01:00.240 --> 00:01:01.920
So I'm going to start with that.

00:01:01.920 --> 00:01:05.540
KnowKings is going to get an invite code here.

00:01:05.540 --> 00:01:10.820
And the way it works is basically through a request.

00:01:10.820 --> 00:01:16.760
And what you saw here is that the first message from the

00:01:16.800 --> 00:01:22.020
Solidarity Social, which goes through the regular BlueSky

00:01:22.110 --> 00:01:25.620
DMs, there's a little message that is automatically app

00:01:25.620 --> 00:01:30.340
ended asking that user to request an invite code.

00:01:30.340 --> 00:01:35.380
And so this person requests an invite code, and Solidarity

00:01:35.380 --> 00:01:41.820
Social then will go to the request code generator section and generates

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:46.780
an invite code, which they can then DM over to the

00:01:46.780 --> 00:01:48.740
other user.

00:01:48.740 --> 00:01:53.650
And that user is now going to go to the Solidarity

00:01:53.750 --> 00:01:57.420
app and start the process of migrating their account.

00:01:57.420 --> 00:02:00.680
And so I'll just give a shout-out here to

00:02:00.680 --> 00:02:06.140
Eurosky's tool EU hall, which we modified and are

00:02:06.140 --> 00:02:07.180
using over here.

00:02:07.180 --> 00:02:11.230
And they basically log in to their existing B-Sky

00:02:11.740 --> 00:02:15.780
Social account, start the process of migration, they put in

00:02:15.780 --> 00:02:18.600
their invite code when it's asked over here.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:23.340
They first select the destination server, Solidar, put in

00:02:23.340 --> 00:02:28.540
their invite code, and select the new handle.

00:02:28.540 --> 00:02:30.610
In this case, we kept the handle the same at Solid

00:02:30.610 --> 00:02:33.980
arity Social, and they're at this step, and they

00:02:34.170 --> 00:02:35.460
're going to kick off the process.

00:02:35.480 --> 00:02:38.430
There's a couple of email codes that they will receive that

00:02:38.430 --> 00:02:40.100
they're going to enter here.

00:02:40.100 --> 00:02:48.190
And as they go through-- you're going to see that

00:02:48.190 --> 00:02:50.720
, that's the second one for the PLC directory update

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:50.980
.

00:02:50.980 --> 00:02:55.700
And then they are going to-- that's success.

00:02:55.700 --> 00:02:57.020
So they have now moved.

00:02:57.020 --> 00:03:03.960
And so now the NoKings is going to log in

00:03:04.600 --> 00:03:07.580
into the Solidar app using these new credentials.

00:03:10.100 --> 00:03:18.060
And so they select the migrating account option.

00:03:18.060 --> 00:03:22.290
And just over here, let me pause to say that we

00:03:22.630 --> 00:03:27.180
need to set up a Matrix account for them.

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:29.210
So they don't know it's a Matrix account, except

00:03:29.210 --> 00:03:30.860
, you know, we tell them, "Do you want

00:03:30.860 --> 00:03:33.750
to do the default option?" So this is a Matrix server

00:03:33.750 --> 00:03:36.860
that is run by the Matrix Foundation based in the EU.

00:03:36.860 --> 00:03:40.230
Or they can actually bring in their own Matrix home server if

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:41.180
they prefer.

00:03:41.180 --> 00:03:44.820
We expect most people will just use the default option.

00:03:49.380 --> 00:03:56.400
And so there's some stuff called recovery keys and so on

00:03:56.520 --> 00:03:57.940
for Matrix, which they don't need to worry about.

00:03:57.940 --> 00:03:59.140
We manage all of that.

00:03:59.140 --> 00:04:03.900
They select-- this is just the onboarding process and they

00:04:03.900 --> 00:04:07.660
are going to have their account.

00:04:07.660 --> 00:04:11.100
And so what I want to show you here is that--

00:04:11.100 --> 00:04:19.320
just going back here-- that what they saw

00:04:19.360 --> 00:04:23.040
in their chat, I think it's not showing it clearly

00:04:23.110 --> 00:04:25.110
here, but there's two sections in their chat, the

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:26.350
secure and the insecure.

00:04:26.460 --> 00:04:29.770
And so now they are actually going to send a message using

00:04:29.770 --> 00:04:38.040
the secure chat to the user that sent

00:04:38.040 --> 00:04:40.680
them the invite code.

00:04:40.780 --> 00:04:41.780
So that's what you're seeing.

00:04:41.780 --> 00:04:45.500
So these messages are the secure chat going to the other user

00:04:45.500 --> 00:04:45.780
.

00:04:45.780 --> 00:04:49.280
And one of the things they can do is actually access this

00:04:49.280 --> 00:04:52.260
secure chat through other Matrix clients.

00:04:52.260 --> 00:04:53.660
So that's what I'm going to show.

00:04:53.660 --> 00:04:55.640
They can bring up a QR code, log in, you

00:04:55.640 --> 00:05:00.100
know, through their phone-- you don't see that part

00:05:00.100 --> 00:05:01.850
here, but that's what's going on.

00:05:02.100 --> 00:05:10.020
And-- oh, it's not moving.

00:05:10.020 --> 00:05:11.220
I'm sorry, yeah.

00:05:11.220 --> 00:05:14.930
And see, that's the phone that's logging in over

00:05:14.930 --> 00:05:15.740
there.

00:05:15.740 --> 00:05:19.140
So they're logging in into the element client on the phone

00:05:19.140 --> 00:05:19.420
.

00:05:19.420 --> 00:05:21.660
And so this is one of the advantages of doing this.

00:05:21.660 --> 00:05:25.210
They can access their DMs through other tools, which actually

00:05:25.210 --> 00:05:26.100
can be quite useful.

00:05:26.100 --> 00:05:28.580
So I can answer some questions about that.

00:05:28.580 --> 00:05:31.520
And the second part is they can actually log in on the

00:05:31.520 --> 00:05:33.620
desktop element client as well.

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.940
They verify again with their phone, which is now verified.

00:05:37.940 --> 00:05:44.100
And now you'll see that, you know, there's

00:05:44.100 --> 00:05:46.100
a message sent from that other client.

00:05:46.100 --> 00:05:49.090
And it's now visible that that last message I can reply

00:05:49.090 --> 00:05:51.540
from there is from the element client.

00:05:51.620 --> 00:05:54.500
So now the last part is just I want to show you

00:05:54.500 --> 00:06:00.420
that it's as easy for the user to actually move back

00:06:00.420 --> 00:06:01.450
to BeskySocial.

00:06:01.460 --> 00:06:03.680
We want to make that easy so that people are, you

00:06:03.680 --> 00:06:06.880
know, confident in experimenting with this, and coming to our

00:06:06.880 --> 00:06:08.260
server, and then going back.

00:06:08.260 --> 00:06:09.860
So that's what this is showing.

00:06:09.860 --> 00:06:12.820
It's actually going to take their account, you know,

00:06:12.820 --> 00:06:13.940
back to BeskySocial.

00:06:13.940 --> 00:06:19.730
So that's the what.

00:06:19.780 --> 00:06:22.980
And I'm happy to take some questions.

00:06:22.980 --> 00:06:26.310
But overall, you know, our goal is that, you

00:06:26.310 --> 00:06:31.640
know, there are people here specifically, for example, the

00:06:31.640 --> 00:06:33.700
people organizing the No Kings protest, etc.

00:06:33.700 --> 00:06:35.620
Today, a lot of them are on Blue Sky.

00:06:35.620 --> 00:06:39.140
They don't have private DMs that, you know,

00:06:39.140 --> 00:06:42.180
they might be interested in that because they want to secure their

00:06:42.180 --> 00:06:43.220
communications.

00:06:43.220 --> 00:06:46.820
But in addition, because they need to actually migrate the account

00:06:46.820 --> 00:06:48.020
and we host it for them.

00:06:49.460 --> 00:06:52.420
It means that, you know, we can also offer them

00:06:52.420 --> 00:06:54.360
more censorship resilience.

00:06:54.420 --> 00:06:57.380
One of the ways we do that is to make it very

00:06:57.380 --> 00:07:00.260
easy for them to migrate their account to another hoster,

00:07:00.260 --> 00:07:03.160
perhaps in a different jurisdiction that can help them, you know

00:07:03.160 --> 00:07:04.100
, have better protection.

00:07:04.660 --> 00:07:06.660
So happy to take a few questions.

00:07:11.220 --> 00:07:20.740
No,

00:07:20.740 --> 00:07:21.440
no, it's the same.

00:07:21.460 --> 00:07:24.060
Yeah, I mean, later you can change it if you

00:07:24.060 --> 00:07:24.340
want.

00:07:24.340 --> 00:07:26.870
But when it goes initially, you go back to your old

00:07:26.870 --> 00:07:27.300
handle.

00:07:27.300 --> 00:07:28.310
Because blue, bsky.

00:07:28.310 --> 00:07:29.380
social reserves it.

00:07:29.380 --> 00:07:30.340
We do the same for them.

00:07:30.340 --> 00:07:32.210
They can actually do another trip back to us and we'll

00:07:32.210 --> 00:07:33.140
keep their handle for them.

00:07:33.140 --> 00:07:33.700
Yeah.

00:07:33.700 --> 00:07:35.220
Yes.

00:07:35.220 --> 00:07:42.840
Okay, so we have some experience with Matrix because, you

00:07:42.840 --> 00:07:45.440
know, I have a software company where we're building real

00:07:45.440 --> 00:07:49.380
estate related apps using the Matrix SDK, etc.

00:07:49.380 --> 00:07:51.860
So we had some many years of experience with that.

00:07:51.860 --> 00:07:54.450
So that's kind of the blue sky part was the new

00:07:54.450 --> 00:07:55.300
part for us.

00:07:55.300 --> 00:07:58.130
But even there, I think we pretty much we have React

00:07:58.130 --> 00:08:00.900
developers and, you know, that's all we really needed

00:08:00.900 --> 00:08:01.380
to know.

00:08:01.380 --> 00:08:02.180
We don't know.

00:08:02.180 --> 00:08:03.810
We didn't have to get too deep into AT Proto

00:08:03.810 --> 00:08:04.020
.

00:08:04.020 --> 00:08:06.660
Yes.

00:08:06.660 --> 00:08:14.730
There's no connection between the blue sky server and the Matrix

00:08:14.730 --> 00:08:15.060
server.

00:08:15.060 --> 00:08:16.260
They're just two different servers.

00:08:17.220 --> 00:08:21.220
They're coming together in this React social app.

00:08:21.220 --> 00:08:24.290
So, you know, what you see is they don't

00:08:24.290 --> 00:08:25.700
know about each other.

00:08:25.700 --> 00:08:26.900
Yeah.

00:08:26.900 --> 00:08:31.210
So that really helps with, you know, being able to

00:08:31.210 --> 00:08:33.300
use all the other Matrix stuff because there's no change.

00:08:33.300 --> 00:08:35.140
They can log in with other clients.

00:08:35.140 --> 00:08:35.780
Yes, go ahead.

00:08:35.780 --> 00:08:42.100
Yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:44.180
So, but they'll have only one credential.

00:08:44.180 --> 00:08:47.220
We generate the Matrix account for them in the background.

00:08:47.220 --> 00:08:50.180
You know, what is the name, managing the credentials.

00:08:50.180 --> 00:08:51.800
Even, you know, in Matrix, there's a second

00:08:51.800 --> 00:08:52.660
more than a password.

00:08:52.660 --> 00:08:54.500
There's even a recovery key.

00:08:54.500 --> 00:08:56.240
We do all of that in the background so they don't

00:08:56.240 --> 00:08:57.060
know anything about it.

00:08:57.060 --> 00:08:58.580
They just remember username, password.

00:08:58.580 --> 00:08:58.980
That's it.

00:08:58.980 --> 00:09:00.820
As they do with blue sky.

00:09:00.820 --> 00:09:08.280
So the way we do it, you know, the secure

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:09.860
way to do it is what I showed over there.

00:09:10.500 --> 00:09:13.680
Show the QR code, and that logs you in into your

00:09:13.680 --> 00:09:14.740
mobile app.

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:16.900
And then after that, if you want to go into the

00:09:16.900 --> 00:09:20.700
desktop app, you know, you actually, again, you

00:09:20.700 --> 00:09:21.540
're already logged in.

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:24.650
So if you open another browser tab, you will actually go

00:09:24.650 --> 00:09:27.700
directly into the app, but you still need to verify,

00:09:27.700 --> 00:09:30.420
and you do the verification against the phone.

00:09:30.420 --> 00:09:32.580
So, yeah, the idea is we don't show them

00:09:32.580 --> 00:09:35.110
the key, but we allow them to basically do what's

00:09:35.110 --> 00:09:35.780
needed.

00:09:35.780 --> 00:09:41.220
Thank you very much.

00:09:41.220 --> 00:09:41.620
Okay.

00:09:41.620 --> 00:09:42.580
Thank you.
